In a spell of warm, sunny and almost calm weather in late February, Dunnock song seemed to issue from every thicket on Inishbofin, County Galway. To my ears, Dunnock song does not 'travel' at a high volume - unlike Song Thrush or even Great tit -  so I decided to conceal my recorder in an area likely to host a visit from a singer. The result is a close-range recording.  The singing male was within two metres of the recorder.  The first ten seconds feature a singing Song Thrush, broadcasting from a garden about 40 m away; the Song  Thrush sings throughout the clip and, when the Dunnock flies off near the end, the Song Thrush can still be heard [from 2:36]. A Wren alarms at 0:11. From 0:16, the clip features Dunnock with, in the background, Skylark and Starlings (that occasionally mimic Curlew).

recordings.rmk:
Interaction of two Dunnocks, recorded with parabolic microphone from a distance of 7 meters with clear line of sight for the whole recording.

First the first bird was alone, singing a loud and full song. Then it started to make very quiet calls, shortly before the second bird joined it and landed a few decimetres to its left. The wingbeats of its arrival might be audible on the recording. The first bird continued to make its quiet calls for a bit before flying away. Then the second bird made quiet calls for a while, before also starting to sing and finally flying away. This song was very different to the first one, mor subsong like.

I interpreted the behaviour as a conflict, possibly territorial, with the second bird displacing the first, but am not sure about this interpretation. They only sat there and sang and called, no bodily interactions.

Everything took place on top of a bush next to some grassland and shallow ponds.

Filtered recording to avoid background noise.

I was sat near a pool watching a flock of Long-tailed Tits (Aegithalos caudatus) and Red-billed Leiothrix (Leiothrix lutea) bathing and drinking.

The Tits flew away and the Red-billed Leiothrix get into the bushes. A bit latter I heard the call from inside the bushes where the Red-billed Leiothrix disappeared. I saw a couple of Red-billed Leiothrix flying away chased by a Dunnock. It perched in an exposed branch and uttered its call.

A bit latter two more Dunnocks showed up and uttered its call.

This is a Great Tit Alarm call but, in sync with each call, there is one or two tiiht... that I couldn't identify from where it was coming. It sounds like a Dunnock calling.

Two Dunnocks synchronising contact notes. One is slightly louder than the other. Mostly, the quickest Dunnock-to-Dunnock exchanges occur in the first 40 seconds of the recording. Note that there is a tendency for the deliveries to develop from two to three notes over the course of the recording: to a certain extent, one Dunnock is copying the lead of the other. Although somewhat difficult to distinguish (that is, count up), some deliveries contain four notes. These (mostly) occur from 1:00 to 1:04 (when a Wren sings).

recordings.file-name: XC358852-Dunnock, autumn calls and song. 13 Oct 2014. IB. 0904hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: Vocalisations from a Dunnock on Inishbofin, off the west of coast of Ireland, in October. Possibly a freshly arrived migrant. The fact that this individual delivered song in autumn suggests that it was a youngster. Although that is speculation, in other songbirds it is generally the case that young males in their first autumn utter snatches of song: as though they are trying out the tongue they were born with. On the other hand, adult males, because the breeding season is months away, don't bother to sing until the courtship season arrives. It is clear that the quality of the song phrases on this recording are shorter and more subdued than song bursts given in spring. Again, that suggests the songster is a novice male. Song phrases begin at 0:10. Before then, typical contact calls can be heard just before the end of the first second (four identical notes run together); at 0:03 (two notes) and 0:08 (four notes).
